d and Kate Tempest she demonstrates the practical use of cognitive frameworks as a means of understanding poetry and its effects. Gavins examines cutting edge concepts in cognition including world-building, conceptual integration, embodiment, and distributed cognition and develops our understanding of key notions in poetics such as poetic metre, performance, metaphor and intertextuality. Each chapter of the book addresses a central poetic notion or feature of poetic style from an innovative cognitive perspective, shedding new light on established ideas about poetic creativity and language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCognitive grammar. 0aEnglish poetryy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPoeticsxPsychological aspects. 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311078041340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147442071640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474420716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474420716/original  a978-3-11-078041-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK